  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Preface to the Huanghua Collection
  author: Lee Seok-hyung
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Ming dynasty has unified all under heaven. The breath of the three luminaries and five sacred peaks mingles without division, surging and billowing forth, concentrating into superior men and worthy talents. From this spring forth scholars of letters and the arts, their brilliance radiating, their excellence fluttering like flags—proclaiming the supreme good governance of an age. How magnificent it is!

    In the twelfth year of the Chenghua era, in the eleventh month of winter, the Emperor established the Crown Prince and issued a decree throughout the realm. The Bureau of Revenue dispatched Qi the Minister, accompanied by Zhang the Envoy, to our kingdom as emissaries. Both gentlemen possess focused and refined bearing; their speech is warm and harmonious; their deportment and conduct accord with propriety. Moreover, they excel in the refinements of poetry, classics, and the six arts. All who have heard their voice and beheld their countenance admire and delight in them without end. How fitting that they encountered sagacious rule and executed their duties with distinction—though their work as emissaries was merely secondary to their true gifts.

    Among their intercourse with scholars and gentlemen, and throughout their journeys of leisure, whether they seized upon objects to stir emotion or gave voice to their inner sentiments, their words flowed into verse—resonant and luminous, springing from the depths of their hearts' own understanding, beyond the reach of mere sensory admirers who linger over landscape and light.

    As the two emissaries prepared to depart, the Crown Prince commanded me, saying: "Our Eastern realm lies distant in remote lands, yet we have received the Emperor's favor through generations. Moreover, in this time of great celebration under heaven, he has specially sent forth scholars of the finest learning, bearing imperial words of great intimacy, granting us singular favor. Truly, the imperial grace knows no bounds.

    "I am moved by the Emperor's profound benevolence and delighted by the virtue of these two emissaries. Yet they must depart swiftly, and what they leave behind—the poems and prose dwelling in all hearts—must not be lost to time. Let them be printed and circulated for eternal transmission."

    Thereupon he commanded me to write this preface.

    I humbly reflect: that talented men emerge in ages of prosperity is the natural order. Yet the way of poetry stirs the human heart even more profoundly. The verses of these two masters are grounded in the utmost rectitude of human nature, refined and substantial in their depths. The Crown Prince, receiving them with delight, was already moved by their refined elegance. Now, perusing their poems anew, his admiration grows ever more fervent. Is this not the testament of poetry's power to move the soul?

    These verses shall be transmitted to future ages alongside the "Huang Huang Zhe Hua" from the Book of Songs—this much is certain. In an age of prosperity, talented men are to the primal breath what substance is to all things. That these two gentlemen have appeared is most fitting. When in days to come they ascend to the highest councils and harmonize the seasons of heaven and earth, and the sage transformation flows forth, uniting all in supreme harmony, it is upon these two worthies that we place our hopes for the Great Elegance of Ming.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three luminaries' (三光) refer to the sun, moon, and stars; the 'five sacred peaks' (五嶽) are the five great mountains that represent cosmic harmony in Chinese tradition.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'six arts' (六藝) traditionally comprise ritual, music, archery, charioteering, calligraphy, and mathematics—the accomplishments of a cultivated person.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'Huang Huang Zhe Hua' alludes to a poem from the Book of Songs celebrating emissaries who carry imperial grace, suggesting these diplomatic verses deserve similar reverence and preservation.
